I don't get it.

30:01.733 --> 30:02.374
I don't get it either.

30:02.514 --> 30:03.115
I don't get it.

30:03.135 --> 30:03.576
That's ridiculous.

30:03.836 --> 30:05.979
I mean, if you really love it.

30:05.999 --> 30:08.763
These are, by definition, ephemeral items.

30:08.783 --> 30:09.564
This is ephemera.

30:10.885 --> 30:12.708
Yeah, it's not like the Mona Lisa.

30:12.728 --> 30:15.111
You know, it's not like Modigliani.

30:15.251 --> 30:17.794
I could see buying a painting.

30:18.956 --> 30:21.960
And I have bought paintings that I like.

30:22.750 --> 30:26.474
And, you know, because of one piece of work, you know, it's like done.

30:26.574 --> 30:31.359
It's really, it really means something all by itself, singularly in the world.

30:31.479 --> 30:35.003
I can see collecting that on some kind of high level.

30:35.383 --> 30:38.506
But, you know, comic books are, like you say, ephemera.

30:38.806 --> 30:40.408
You have goals for yourself, I guess.

30:42.670 --> 30:50.498
It would please you when all is said and done to be ranked and considered with the crates of the genre.

30:50.699 --> 30:51.019
Oh, yeah.

30:51.235 --> 30:54.238
Talk to me about that.

30:54.258 --> 30:57.641
Well, you know, I'm in there.

30:58.081 --> 30:59.122
Do you read them, by the way?

30:59.182 --> 31:00.463
I've read all of them.

31:00.483 --> 31:01.264
I've read all the greats.

31:01.884 --> 31:04.046
I mean, I haven't read some of the people.

31:04.106 --> 31:06.208
But, you know, there are a lot of people who are just wonderful.

31:06.888 --> 31:14.175
The guys in America, Chandler Hammett, McDonald, later Charles Williford, who I just think is brilliant.

31:14.715 --> 31:15.556
He is excellent.

31:15.716 --> 31:16.517
I'm sorry he died.

31:17.538 --> 31:19.639
He's such a great writer.

31:19.659 --> 31:20.280
Isn't he a little cockfighter?

31:21.037 --> 31:22.339
Jeff Wilford?

31:22.359 --> 31:23.521
Was he down in Florida?

31:23.741 --> 31:23.941
Yeah.

31:23.961 --> 31:24.622
I haven't read that.

31:24.642 --> 31:26.525
I reviewed that when I first started reviewing.

31:26.545 --> 31:27.226
It wasn't a mystery.

31:27.266 --> 31:28.148
It was just a novel.

31:28.348 --> 31:30.090
Wonderful, about cockfighting.

31:30.110 --> 31:30.872
Spectacular.

31:30.892 --> 31:32.093
His writing is so good.

31:32.113 --> 31:37.001
It's just like, you know, I just, I just, it's just, you read it and it's just funny.

31:37.141 --> 31:40.646
It's like, and you know, with anybody who can make you laugh, Sam doesn't simply choose Parker.

31:40.666 --> 31:42.429
He has a great ability to make you laugh.

31:43.570 --> 31:47.737
Tim and James Lee Burke, you know, you can say anything you want about genre.

31:47.757 --> 31:48.698
I mean, uh,

31:49.505 --> 31:53.251
This guy's a novelist who can't write about any damn thing he wants.

31:53.531 --> 31:54.853
No, it's true.

31:55.374 --> 31:57.237
And I'm sure I'm being introduced to you now.

31:57.257 --> 32:00.562
I have to confess, you know, I write about authors all the time.

32:00.582 --> 32:02.425
I can't say I've read the shelf on Mosley.

32:03.266 --> 32:05.269
That's right.

32:05.489 --> 32:10.837
But once I get into a person and I like them, then I inevitably do.

32:11.859 --> 32:14.503
All right, like I read all of Rick Stout and all of someone else.

32:14.523 --> 32:16.626
It took me years, you know.

32:17.112 --> 32:19.875
But how do you see yourself developing as a writer?

32:20.216 --> 32:20.776
How do you mean that?

32:21.377 --> 32:24.961
Developing as a, you know, maturing, developing, changing.

32:25.241 --> 32:25.602
I don't know.

32:26.223 --> 32:26.563
I don't know.

32:26.583 --> 32:28.545
Otherwise it becomes stale.

32:28.906 --> 32:31.589
Yeah, well, it can't be the same stuff.

32:31.629 --> 32:38.817
You know, part of the thing that I have for this series is I don't, I age easily, and each book is, you know,

32:39.151 --> 32:41.634
somewhat older, though I'm going to spend a while in the 60s.

32:41.654 --> 32:43.236
I'm going to start it from the age of 28.

32:43.296 --> 32:46.901
I'm going to go up to the age of 75, 76, whatever.

32:47.001 --> 32:49.584
So that's one way that... So he will age with you?

32:49.745 --> 32:50.225
Yeah.

32:50.265 --> 32:52.268
In real time or three quarters?

32:52.288 --> 32:53.129
In real time.

32:53.189 --> 32:53.730
A lot less.

32:53.810 --> 32:57.735
I think I'll probably be finished with the series in 10 to 12 years.

32:58.616 --> 33:04.083
Oh, so at that point you will have, you will be developing into... I'll be like, I'll be 50-something.

33:04.483 --> 33:06.125
Yeah, but I mean, you'll be writing other things.

33:06.386 --> 33:06.846
Oh, yeah, yeah.

33:06.926 --> 33:07.968
I'll be writing other stuff.

33:08.248 --> 33:08.989
You know, I'll be

33:09.222 --> 33:10.483
There's a lot of stuff I want to do.

33:10.824 --> 33:20.693
As a writer itself, I'm so interested in it because one thing that I love about doing work that you love, that you grow by doing the work.

33:21.254 --> 33:31.324
If you really are interested in the work and you're interested in how it's going to develop and where it's going to go, you just grow and the work changes and grows.

33:31.524 --> 33:34.126
So where I'll end up, I don't know.

33:34.547 --> 33:35.888
Who I'll be, I don't know.

33:36.020 --> 33:41.026
I expect to have some footing in the genre, whatever that is.

33:41.466 --> 33:45.291
But I also expect to go into many other aspects of writing.

33:45.531 --> 33:48.354
This thing of writing about the blues is another aspect of black life.

33:48.475 --> 33:53.440
I think that the blues is the 20th century idea of tragedy.

33:54.321 --> 33:57.145
And so I'm talking about that in this book.

33:57.826 --> 33:59.968
In other books, I'll be doing other stuff like that.

34:01.045 --> 34:05.992
Is this a longer novel, say, than the blues novel?

34:06.072 --> 34:07.434
It's very hard to tell.

34:07.474 --> 34:08.515
It's very hard to tell.

34:08.555 --> 34:11.279
This book is 80,000 words.

34:11.539 --> 34:14.403
The blues novel won't be more than 100,000.

34:14.924 --> 34:18.389
It might be less than 8,000.

34:19.430 --> 34:20.792
Writing long books...

34:21.278 --> 34:22.720
There has to be a good reason for it.

34:22.740 --> 34:24.322
There used to be a good reason for it.

34:24.342 --> 34:26.725
My book is 255,000 books.

34:26.945 --> 34:28.227
My God.

34:28.247 --> 34:29.288
Well, it's nonfiction.

34:29.429 --> 34:30.871
What can I tell you?

34:30.991 --> 34:31.892
Oh, yeah.

34:31.972 --> 34:33.194
I covered 2,500 years.

34:33.254 --> 34:34.936
How can you not write that?

34:34.956 --> 34:36.097
No, but that's the point, though.

34:36.137 --> 34:44.188
I mean, I think that, like, when people were writing novels at the beginning of the century and into the last century, they had a lot of work to do.

34:44.228 --> 34:46.611
They had to talk about, you know,

34:47.350 --> 34:51.774
places that people had never been, people that they had never met, thoughts that they had never had.

34:52.134 --> 34:55.778
And there were no competing distractions either for the reader's time.

34:55.858 --> 34:56.498
Sure, well, there's that.

34:56.999 --> 34:59.501
But also those distractions also fill in that thing.

34:59.521 --> 35:14.455
Like, you know, if you want to know about the Himalayas, probably if that's a reason that you're going to read something, you might do just as well to look at a National Geographic special on the Himalayas.

35:14.485 --> 35:20.812
But if you're writing about a character in the Hamalayas, really you're talking about the character themselves and how they're developing, how they relate.

35:20.832 --> 35:21.793
And that's shorter work.

35:21.853 --> 35:23.275
It's more condensation.

35:23.475 --> 35:27.399
See, why is it that I can't read James Michener with pleasure?

35:27.419 --> 35:29.241
Because for precisely that reason.

35:29.562 --> 35:35.428
If I want to go to Hawaii, Hawaii, go there.

35:35.448 --> 35:37.010
Or know the history of Hawaii.

35:37.030 --> 35:37.690
It's interesting.

35:37.831 --> 35:39.092
I respect him.

35:39.342 --> 35:47.070
tremendously, but he doesn't engage me as a writer of fiction.

35:47.250 --> 35:55.279
I like The Godfather, a big old rambly book, and I like going through all that stuff because the history is more personal history.

35:55.299 --> 35:57.381
It's not the kind of history you're going to go read somewhere.

35:57.901 --> 36:04.048
It's not the history of Sicily, but it's the history of a family, a mafia family from Sicily to New York.

36:04.408 --> 36:07.932
I could slow down for something like that.

36:09.110 --> 36:30.747
Yeah, I've been told many times.

36:31.688 --> 36:32.029
Really?

36:32.212 --> 36:35.038
And everybody tells me that you're distributed everywhere.

36:35.358 --> 36:36.340
No kidding.

36:36.761 --> 36:37.803
I'm doing it myself.

36:38.665 --> 36:40.829
Entrepreneurially, if there's such a word.

36:42.472 --> 36:47.723
But I got myself a... What are the vital signs for you?

36:47.783 --> 36:49.807
What do you hear from readers?

36:49.827 --> 36:52.412
And does it influence what you're doing?

36:52.432 --> 36:53.815
Well, you know...

36:54.014 --> 36:54.755
That's interesting.

36:54.875 --> 36:56.757
I hear a lot from readers.

36:56.797 --> 37:02.622
Mainly, I don't... And then as a corollary, pardon me, but do you have a picture of who your reader is?

37:03.523 --> 37:03.804
No.

37:03.944 --> 37:06.666
I mean, I do, but it's a very broad readership.

37:06.747 --> 37:09.669
It's in three distinct categories, I think.

37:09.689 --> 37:17.597
There are the mystery readers, which is a very broad range of people, from bricklayers to physicists.

37:18.578 --> 37:22.502
The other day, somebody was like, I've got a book, and I was signing a book for this long-haired guy, and somebody said,

37:22.786 --> 37:27.232
This guy was one of the foremost geneticists, like in the country.

37:27.453 --> 37:31.278
But, like, I didn't know this guy on a bicycle.

37:31.298 --> 37:33.882
But, like, I'm signing his book, you know, and he's reading it.

37:33.902 --> 37:35.444
You know, and then, you know, just all kinds of other people.

37:35.464 --> 37:36.466
That's in the mystery world.

37:36.826 --> 37:49.705
Then there's a world of black people, the African-Americans, who, you know, are kind of hungry to hear or to be corroborated in their knowledge of that oral history that we were talking about, who come and, you know, just talk about it and say, yeah, I had...

37:49.786 --> 38:12.705
parents like that or i'm like that or i'm interested in that that kind of people and then the kind of a general literary audience i i have you know i've been developing uh over this period of time people who read it on the beach and then they take it back to their house and read it you know you had a terrific paperback sale of course which uh which cuts across all yeah right yeah that that you know that's the whole thing that paperback is doing very well and

38:12.888 --> 38:17.313
So, you know, that's going really good.

38:18.053 --> 38:24.240
And, you know, but, you know, also, you know, interestingly, just something else, at the ABA.

38:24.440 --> 38:26.722
Did you go to the ABA?

38:26.742 --> 38:28.144
Yeah, I was there.

38:28.444 --> 38:29.425
I was there a lot.

38:29.445 --> 38:36.812
But one of the things, on June 5th, on the Sunday, I had a little article in the book review.

38:37.413 --> 38:37.934
It was page two.

38:38.194 --> 38:40.036
It was an article about racism and publishing.

38:40.056 --> 38:41.217
The TVR or the LA Times?

38:41.817 --> 38:42.338
LA Times.

38:43.060 --> 38:47.484
it was about racism and publishing.

38:47.504 --> 38:50.147
Because, you know, you have the publishing world, but there are no people of color in it.

38:50.307 --> 38:52.029
A few black people, and then nobody else.

38:52.089 --> 38:54.891
Like, no Puerto Ricans, no, you know, Native Americans.

38:54.911 --> 38:57.334
Very few Asians, which is kind of surprising to me.

38:57.354 --> 38:58.495
But all these people, they're just not there.

38:58.935 --> 39:00.036
And I did write an article about it.

39:00.056 --> 39:05.441
It just said, you know, it's an aspect of liberal passive racism.

39:05.922 --> 39:07.163
And I think it was a good article.

39:07.243 --> 39:10.266
Because I don't think I said anything that was untrue.

39:10.600 --> 39:15.686
or anything anybody could call a liar could argue with, which I think is the big thing about journalism when you do it.

39:16.367 --> 39:20.773
Because if anybody can negate one moment of it, then they can negate everything that you said.

39:21.414 --> 39:23.877
And so I was very happy with the writing.

39:23.937 --> 39:26.740
And I don't really see it much different than any other kind of writing I do.

39:27.061 --> 39:32.187
And it was wonderful because maybe 40 or 50 people came up to me and said thanks.

39:32.352 --> 39:33.073
Isn't that great?

39:33.093 --> 39:36.296
He just said, thanks for writing that, because we want to see the truth out there.

39:36.316 --> 39:38.379
It is the payoff of journalism, by the way.

39:38.679 --> 39:39.500
It is immediate.

39:39.900 --> 39:52.754
The response is, a buddy of mine who's a writer and also a former jazz musician, he said, the thing about performing on the stage is that you hear it immediately.

39:52.975 --> 39:57.320
If they've enjoyed what you've done, the applause is there.

39:57.360 --> 40:00.503
But when you're writing, it can be two or three years before

40:00.685 --> 40:02.107
There's any kind of a sense.

40:02.407 --> 40:03.809
Or if you live that long.

40:03.989 --> 40:05.671
Or if you live that long.

40:05.691 --> 40:08.174
Herman Melville, one of the people.

40:08.194 --> 40:08.694
Exactly.

40:10.476 --> 40:10.957
Okay.

40:11.337 --> 40:13.480
Well, I think we've got a pretty good little interview here.

40:13.620 --> 40:13.860
All right.

40:14.141 --> 40:16.944
If you give me an address, I'll be pleased to send you some copies.

40:17.104 --> 40:18.286
37 Carmine Street.

40:18.306 --> 40:19.127
C-A-R-M-I-N-E?

40:20.028 --> 40:20.288
Yeah.

